Six novels have been nominated for the Booker Prize, Britain's most prestigious fiction award. 
Bookmakers say the favorite is Japanese author Kazuo Ishiguro's "The Remains of the Day" 
about a butler's travels through Britain's West Country. An odds maker gave it 7 to 4 odds.

More interest in the award than ever before is expected because of last year's controversy over 
Salmon Rushdie's "Satanic Verses". Rushdie lost out last year to Australian author Peter Carey 
for his "Oscar and Lucinda". Rushdie, a British citizen, has been hiding since February 14 when 
the Iranian leader Khomeini ordered him killed for blaspheming Islam in "Satanic Verses".</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d117"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891026-0208"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Japanese writer Kazuo Ishiguro won the 1989 Booker Prize, Britain's top literary award, for his 
novel, "The Remains of the Day", a love story about a butler's English vacation. It explores the 
vexed themes of class, tradition, and duty. Ishiguro, 39, arrived in England at age 6 and now 
lives in south London. He was a finalist for the Booker Prize in 1986.

After receiving the prize, Ishiguro paid tribute to Salmon Rushdie, the 1988 runner-up for the 
award, who went into hiding in February when threatened with death by Moslems who said his 
novel, "The Satanic Verses" blasphemed their faith.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d117"
TYPE="PERDOC"
