The Booker Prize, Britain's literary event of the year is guaranteed to boost sales of the chosen 
novel.  The winning author receives a check for #20,000 ($38,000) sponsored by Booker, an 
international food and agriculture business. Book Trust, a charity promoting reading and books, 
administers the prize.

British publishers submit three new novels by British and Commonwealth writers. A 
management committee of authors, booksellers, librarians, and the sponsors choose a jury of 
five: a writer and/or an academic, politician, editor or critic. Each juror reads every book and 
meets with other jurists to select six finalists.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d117"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP901016-0112"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Critic and novelist Antonia Byatt won the Booker Prize, Britain's most prestigious literary award 
for "Possession", one of the year's six finalists in the 21-year old competition. She received 
$39,000 and earlier this month received the $43,000 Times-Aer Lingus prize for international 
faction for the same work. The Booker Prize was announced at a banquet in London's 
Elizabethan Guildhall, seat of the city's Lord Mayor. Her book is a tale of two young scholars 
investigating the lives of a pair of imaginary Victorian poets by retracing the poets' journeys 
across England and to France. She has published five novels since 1964.</SUM>

<SUM
