The annual Booker ballyhoo got going yesterday when the judges for this year's #20,000 prize 
for British (and Commonwealth) fiction announced the shortlist. The prize is no longer the 
richest literary award but it guarantees great prestige and sales for the winner and brings the 
novel to public attention.

Critics say the brouhaha distorts the annual fiction industry and the intense media hype of the 
shortlisted authors does a disservice to other gifted but unlisted authors. For weeks, London's 
literati have been betting on Michael Ondaatje's "The English Patient" and last night the 
bookmakers made it the 5-2 favorite.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d117"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT943-5106"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="G">

The shortlist of six for the #20,000 Booker Prize for fiction prompted the publishing industry to 
comment that some on the list "are B-team writers at best" and that others "don't make the 
grade". This is surprising commentary given it is a bumper year for new fiction fulfilling the 
criteria--English language and non-American.

There was some traditional controversy when it was revealed that an author whose novel had 
made the longlist was actually the wife of a Booker judge. But critics say it's the final list, not 
the controversy, which must have a final death blow to the Booker.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d117"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT943-3897"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="G">

This week, the shortlist for the hypothetical 1894 Booker Prize consists of six classic and 
bestseller books, which stirred the fin de siecle world and remain compelling today. The 
retrospective raises questions about how the relationship between literature and society has 
changed in the past 100 years.

Victorians were lovers of contemporary fiction. Middle class writers and readers were more 
homogenous and more certain of their place in the mainstream. The novel was their political and 
intellectual forum. Modernism weakened 20th century belief in the novel and the dominance of 
film and television has made novels a more marginal form.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d117"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT944-16774"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="G">

After hours of deliberation last night, the #20,000 Booker Prize for fiction, as it always has in its 
26-year history, provoked controversy when it went to James Kelman for "How Late It Was, 
How Late", the story of a Scottish lowlife narrated in Glaswegian dialect. Bookseller dismissed 
the whole shortlist as narcoleptic.

The chairman of the Booker judges acknowledged heated deliberation. He said the book might 
be deemed inaccessible and went on record with a rousing condemnation of contemporary 
fiction. Another judge was attacked for failing to reveal a novelist being considered for the award 
was, in fact, his wife.</SUM>
